<font color="#FF0000">PARADOX</font><br>
<tt>Fri Jan  2 11:50:25 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
Although the answers to my question (Dec. 29) were expected, I thank Cook Barela for some details that I did not know.  This information indicates that there is a paradox in the protest movement, and I would like to know whether anyone can reconcile the apparent contradictions.<br>
   Obviously, if the U. S. had been ruled by a communist or a fascist government, the protest movement would have been treated differently than it was.  Contrary to some statements, there were protests in Germany during the Second World War.  In addition to the senior officers who tried to blow Hitler up, there was a group of students in Munich who called their movement the White Rose.  They passed out pamphlets denouncing the government.  The Gestapo went right to work to find them.  At their trial, they were loudly denounced as traitors by both the prosecutors and judges.  A few days later, they were beheaded in a guillotine.  A large number of clergymen were placed in concentration camps, where they were executed or died due to the conditions of imprisonment.<br>
   In all communist countries, protests of any kind have been rare because protest is correctly regarded as a form of suicide.  When the general dissatisfaction reaches the breaking point, events occur such as those at Tien An Men Square in 1989, Prague in 1968, North Vietnam from 1956 to 1958, Budapest in 1956, and Berlin in 1953.  Until the Russian people successfully stood up to the tanks in 1990, these protests had always been choked in blood.<br>
   In their writings, communists have designated such ideals as freedom of speech, assembly, and the press as values of the bourgeoisie and described Americans as weak and decadent for having them.  The communist government in North Vietnam oppressed all opposition and won the war.  In South Vietnam, the people wished for the &quot;decadent&quot; American ideals and achieved some degree of success in gaining them. If this were not true, they could not have protested, which they obviously did.  Their desire for freedom was later evidenced by the flight of millions of South Vietnamese, most of whom would up spending the rest of their lives in wretched poverty in refugee camps or died when their ships were attacked by pirates.  The United States itself also permitted protest on a major scale, although the voters in 1972 overwhelmingly rejected the &quot;peace&quot; candidate for president and in this way, showed that they did not agree with the protesters. However, according to the claims of former protesters who give themselves credit for &quot;ending the war&quot;, the protests brought about the defeat of the United States and South Vietnam.<br>
   The paradox is that the former protesters are crediting themselves with a great achievement for having helped a government come to power that would not have permitted their movements to exist if it had ruled the United States.  If a communist faction had ruled the United States and were waging war with another communist faction in North Vietnam, students passing out anti-war literature, organizing protests, or demanding that the war be ended would simply have been rounded up by the police and never seen again.  At Kent State, four protesters were killed after some members of the National Guard lost their nerve after being pelted with large rocks. What would have happened if such a protest had occurred under a communist regime?  Under these circumstances, the communists would have placed troops at strategic positions to get the protesters in a cross fire, and all would simply have been shot down.  Any survivors would have been arrested and shipped off to some cold and remote part of the country to work at hard labor in excess of 12 hours each day, attend re-education lectures, and write and re-write personal confessions of crimes against the people.  Release could be expected only after the prison officials were certain that the prisoner would never open his mouth again. Informers from among the students, probably wearing masks to avoid recognition, would have been sent to point their fingers at those they thought were sympathetic to the demonstrators.  The persons they indicated would also have been sent off to the labor and re-education camps or perhaps sent to Vietnam as soldiers under punishment.  Commanders would have been instructed to use them for such duties as walking through mine fields to clear them quickly or walking point where ambushes were expected.  The press would neither report casualties from the war nor any activites of protesters.  The police would occasionally be praised for arresting bands of traitors.<br>
   Under these circumstances, there would have been no protest movement, and the Unites States, like North Vietnam, would have been able to send troops to Vietnam indefinately, waging a war without end and without regard for losses.  However, because America was not ruled by communists or fascists at the time, its people valued the rights of free speech and assembly and therefore permitted a protest movement to help a regime come to power against the will of the governed and suppress those freedoms that permitted such a protest movement to exist in the first place.<br>
   Paradox: a movement that works take the freedom away that permits the movement itself to exist.<br><br>

